The density of optical states ρ is a factor of potentially large influence on the radiative decay. It depends on the refractive index of the QD, the shape of the QD, and the polarization of the emission, as well as on the photonic environment of the QD. For example, photonic crystals [238] or plasmonic structures [239] can enhance or suppress radiative decay of QDs. For QDs dispersed in an organic medium, as they are commonly prepared and analyzed, the density of optical states ρ is determined by the refractive index of the medium n and the refractive index contrast with the QD material itself nQD:2ρ=n3n22n2+nQD22.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
